  "translation_social_labels_only": "其实，陛下，如果您还记得，我们最终确实倾向于用意大利语。"
}

{
  "social_guidance_summary": "Mozart maintains a deferential and eager tone when addressing the Opera Director, acknowledging the listener's higher institutional power. The use of polite pronouns and a formal address reflects the patron-artist relationship and Mozart's desire for professional approval. The translation preserves his slight hesitation and immediate compliance with the director's inquiry.",
  "translation_social_labels_only": "我——我不觉得您已经看过了，总监先生。还没有。我是说，这还是件——当然，我立刻就拿给您看。"
}

{
  "social_guidance_summary": "Mozart adopts a respectful and earnest tone when addressing his superiors, who hold higher institutional power as his patrons. He is eager to please and defensive about his artistic integrity, resulting in a polite yet slightly frantic register. The translation balances this deference with his characteristic enthusiasm while accurately rendering his stammered explanation.",
  "translation_social_labels_only": "为什么不呢？这戏非常有魅力。我是说，我并没真的展示姬妾们露出她们的……她们的……！这绝非下流之事！陛下，这非常符合道德，充满了正统的德意志美德。我敢发誓，绝对如此！"
}

{
  "social_guidance_summary": "Salieri is addressing Emperor Joseph II, requiring a highly formal and deferential tone appropriate for a court setting. The speaker uses honorifics and a humble posture to acknowledge the listener's absolute authority while politely framing his curiosity as a request for enlightenment from a superior.",
  "translation_social_labels_only": "陛下，请恕我冒昧，您觉得这些会是什么？身为外国人，我很想向您请教。"
}

{
